GPGPU-Sim TUTORIALS
GPGPU-Sim is a cycle-level simulator for modeling GPU microarchitectures and running CUDA or OpenCL workloads without the need for physical hardware. Below are the primary tutorials and resources for getting started. 
1. Official Getting Started Guide
The most direct way to start is the GPGPU-Sim Manual, which covers the core workflow: 
University of Wisconsin–Madison
University of Wisconsin–Madison
Installation: Requirements include gcc, make, zlib, bison, and flex. You must set environment variables like GPGPUSIM_ROOT and CUDAHOME in your .bashrc.
Building: Use make in the root directory to build the simulator.
Running: To run a CUDA application, you typically link it dynamically by adding the GPGPU-Sim library path to LD_LIBRARY_PATH. 
University of Wisconsin–Madison
University of Wisconsin–Madison
 +4
2. Video Tutorials (Academic)
For a structured classroom approach, the ECE 695 GPGPU-Sim Tutorial series is highly recommended: 
Part 1: Overview: Focuses on the architectural components modeled, including the SIMT core and memory system.
Part 2: Software (SW): Covers the interface to CUDA API, PTX parsing, and simulator startup details. 
YouTube
YouTube
 +1
3. Modern Setup: Docker & Accel-Sim
Recent research often uses Accel-Sim, a fork of GPGPU-Sim that supports modern NVIDIA architectures like Volta and Ampere. 
Accel-Sim
Accel-Sim
 +1
Docker Approach: You can skip manual dependency management by pulling a pre-configured image: docker pull pli33/gpgpusim:cuda_3.1_3.
Quickstart Guide: The SST QuickStart provides instructions for integrating GPGPU-Sim with the Structural Simulation Toolkit (SST) for full-system simulation. 
CliffsNotes
CliffsNotes
 +1
4. Advanced Configuration & Visualization
AerialVision: A performance visualizer included with GPGPU-Sim. Run python aerialvision.py to plot data from your simulation logs.
Configuration Files: You must provide a gpgpusim.config file in your application's directory to define GPU parameters like the number of shader cores or DRAM timing. 
mail.ncku.edu.tw
mail.ncku.edu.tw
 +3
For more community support, you can join the official GPGPU-Sim Google Group to ask specific technical questions. 
