NASIC EXMAP;LE WITH CODE
To run a basic example in GPGPU-Sim, you need three components in your working directory: a CUDA source file (.cu), a configuration file (gpgpusim.config), and an interconnect configuration (config_fermi_islip.icnt). 
GitHub
GitHub
 +1
1. Simple CUDA Code: Vector Addition 
Create a file named vector_add.cu. This code adds two vectors of size 4096 on the GPU. 
NVIDIA Developer
NVIDIA Developer
 +2
cpp
#include <stdio.h>
#include <cuda_runtime.h>

// Vector Addition Kernel
__global__ void vector_add(const float *a, const float *b, float *c, int n) {
    int idx = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;
    if (idx < n) c[idx] = a[idx] + b[idx];
}

int main() {
    int n = 4096;
    size_t size = n * sizeof(float);
    // ... Host/Device memory allocation, data copy, and kernel launch (1D grid) ...
    // ... (See for full code example) ...
    return 0;
}
Use code with caution.

2. Required Setup Steps
Ensure the simulator is linked properly to intercept CUDA calls: 
Stanford University
Stanford University
 +1
Compile: nvcc vector_add.cu -o vectorAdd -lcudart
Configurations: Copy config files from $GPGPUSIM_ROOT/configs/tested-cfgs/SM2_GTX480/ to your run directory
Run: Set LD_LIBRARY_PATH to the GPGPU-Sim library and execute: ./vectorAdd 
Stanford University
Stanford University
 +3
3. Verifying Execution
If successful, the terminal will display "GPGPU-Sim: *** Initialization ***" followed by detailed performance statistics, including IPC, DRAM utilization, and cache hit rates. 
